Various leaders have eulogised the late William ole Ntimama as a fearless and dedicated leader who fought for the rights of the Maasai community and Kenyans.Speaking at a requiem Mass at All Saints Cathedral in Nairobi, Interior CS Joseph Nkaissery described the late former minister as a man who did not mince his words. He is one man who meant his word; he gave us hope and he spoke his mind, Nkaissery said. Cord leader Raila Odinga said he worked with Mr Ntimama and that the country had lost a great leader.Mr Odinga recalled Mr Ntimama s role in protecting the Mau forest and his fight to ensure the Truth, Justice and Reconciliation Commission (TJRC)To united Kenyans was exemplary. Relatives of the late William ole Ntimama bow in prayer during a requiem Mass at All Saints Cathedral in Nairobi on September 13, 2016. PHOTO | JEFF ANGOTE | NATION MEDIA GROUPMr Odinga said the TJRC report submitted to President Kenyatta in May 2013 should be discussed in Parliament and endorsed as a way of honouring Mr Ntimama. Among the report's key findings was that violence between different ethnic groups in Kenya was sparked by land-related injustices that have not been addressed since independence. [Mr Nitimama] was very passionate about historical injustices meted out against the Maa community, he said. Edward Lowassa, a presidential candidate in Tanzania's last election, said Mr Ntimama championed land rights for the Maasai. email print email print A cleansing ceremony for the family was also conducted.Kenya is lobbying against the planned agreement between US and 12 Asian states for fear of losingPeres will be buried next to Rabin, who was assassinated in 1995 by a Jewish extremist opposed to